		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id71f53e7682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>4:13.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Search and seizure—Warrant requirement</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<?page no="123"?>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>All persons enjoy the privilege against unreasonable search and seizure of their person and property under the Fourth Amendment of the United States Constitution. <eos/>
						<bos/>The Georgia Constitution[<footnote.reference refid="I77c93d2074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] and the Georgia Code[<footnote.reference refid="I77c93d2174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] provide similar protections.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Both federal and state law prefer searches be pursued under a valid search warrant, yet even in warranted searches evidence might be excluded due to a defect in the issuance or execution of the warrant itself.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I77c9643074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] For example, a search warrant is invalid where it does not state with particularity items to be seized. <eos/>
						<bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-serial-number="2041759842" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ibde3f99274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Bryant v. State,</ital>
						</cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I77c9b25074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court found that a warrant is invalid where it lists only a description and an address of the home to be searched but does not provide a list of items to be seized even where a basis exists for procuring the warrant.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Both the United States and Georgia Constitutions require probable cause for the issuance of a warrant which is more than more than mere suspicion but less than “proof beyond a reasonable doubt.”[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I77c9d96074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] To obtain a warrant, <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“[t]here need only be probable cause to believe that evidence of a crime has been secreted on specific premises. <eos/>
						<bos/>Probable cause exists where the facts and circumstances would warrant a man of reasonable caution in believing that the evidence sought is in the place described.”<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I77c9d96174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] If a warrant is obtained pursuant to an affidavit based on information from a confidential informant, the magistrate must independently determine the reliability of the information and the informant.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I77c9d96274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>
						<cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST17-5-21" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ibde6438074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 17-5-21</cite.query> sets forth the grounds for issuance of a search warrant. <eos/>
						<bos/>Further, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="ES" w-normalized-cite="GAST17-15-22" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ibde6438174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. §§ 17-15-22</cite.query> to <cite.query w-src-number="0287018126" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="ES" w-normalized-cite="GAST17-15-28" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ibde6438274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">17-15-28</cite.query> provide the statutory framework for the application, issuance, and execution of search warrants.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>With respect to evidentiary practice, practitioners should file a motion to suppress if a <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“search and seizure with a warrant was illegal because the warrant is insufficient on its face, there was not probable cause for the issuance of the warrant, or the warrant was illegally executed”<end.quote refid="QT_0002"/> within the scope of the Georgia Code or the state or federal constitutions.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I77c9d96374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<?page no="124"?>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>However, be aware that when a search warrant affidavit contains incorrect information, and the court concludes that if that information is set aside the affidavit still contains sufficient facts to establish probable cause, then the search conducted pursuant to the warrant is lawful.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I77ca007074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
